IFC - Qual Panel:
Informed Consent Form

Title of Study: Do Canadians Understand the Risk of False Confessions? 


INTRODUCTION 

My name is Dr. Marc Patry and I am a full-time faculty member in the Psychology Department
at Saint Mary’s University and supervisor of this research project. Emily Rybak is the principal
investigator in this research and is a current Master’s student at Saint Mary’s and Pierre-Olivier
Couture is the co-investigator of this research and is a current Undergraduate student at Saint
Mary’s University. This research has received partial internal funding. I would like to invite you
to participate in this research study regarding the knowledge Canadian’s have concerning risks of
false confessions during police interrogations.



PURPOSE OF THIS RESEARCH 

This research aims to examine the level of knowledge that Canadians currently have regarding police interrogations, and any factors that may or may not contribute to those interrogations resulting in false confessions.



PARTICIPATION 

Anybody who is 19 or older and a Canadian Citizen may participate. You will be asked to follow a secure link online to complete this study on Qualtrics. As this is an online study, you may participate from the location of your choice. Participants will be asked to complete a short survey containing questions related to their knowledge of police interrogations and questions. The study is expected to last approximately 15 minutes.



POTENTIAL BENEFITS 

Benefits of this study may include contributing to psycho-legal research and potentially the legal system, by providing information regarding laypersons knowledge on an important topic. In addition, this study may benefit you by increasing your knowledge and awareness of interrogation and confession research.



POTENTIAL RISKS FOR PARTICIPANTS 

Some questions in this study could result in feelings of discomfort or emotional distress. Should you feel uncomfortable during this study, you are able to withdraw at any point without negative consequence. As a Saint Mary’s student, if you experience feelings of discomfort, we encourage you to utilize the free counseling services on campus. Counseling services are located on the fourth floor of the Saint Mary’s Student Center, should you wish to visit, or you can contact them by telephone at: 902-420-5615 or by email at: counselling@smu.ca.

Should you wish to obtain help outside of the university, we encourage you to contact the Mental Health Mobile Crisis Team. This is a free service that assists anyone experiencing a mental health crisis or mental distress. The Mental Health Mobile Crisis Team can be reached at 1-888- 429-8167. You can also contact the Halifax mental health crisis support at 902-429-8167 or Wellness Together Canada at 1-866-585-0445.



PARTICIPATION COMPENSATION 
You will be compensated the amount you agreed upon before you entered into the survey. 



ANONYMITY
All the information that you provide will be subject to anonymity. Online data will be collected
via Qualtrics and will be securely stored on Canadian servers. Once data collection is complete
the data will be downloaded and removed from the server. The data will be downloaded and
stored on personal, password protected, computers belonging to the researchers. None of the data
will be connected to any personal identifiers such as names. All downloaded data from the study
questionnaire will be stored in perpetuity following the dissemination of the project.



STUDY RESULTS 

On completion of the study the researchers will create a summary report. It is anticipated that this will be available by August 2024. This research is being conducted with the expectation that it will potentially lead to a publication as well as conference presentations. If you are interested in the study’s findings, please contact the researchers following the completion of the survey. If you contact the researchers indicating that you are interested in the study’s findings, your contact information will be confidentially saved and stored on personal, password protected, computers belonging to the researchers, and you will be contacted with the disseminated results when the study is complete. The researchers will also be disseminating the findings amongst the facilities that assisted in the recruitment of participants. Please note that as all data from the main survey are anonymous, we cannot provide individualized results.



HOW CAN I WITHDRAW FROM THIS STUDY? 

Participants who are recruited through Qualtrics will not receive the compensation you agreed upon before entering the survey if you chose to withdraw before completing the survey. Should you wish to withdraw during the study, you may simply exit the web browser. Upon submission of your survey, researchers will no longer be able to exclude your data from analyses, as we will not be collecting identifying information in the main survey and therefore will be unable to identify the data as yours.



QUESTIONS & CONTACT FOR CONCERNS 

Should you have any further questions about this study, please feel free to contact Emily Rybak (Emily.Rybak@smu.ca), Pierre-Olivier Couture (pierre-olivier.couture@smu.ca) or Dr. Marc Patry (Marc.Patry@smu.ca; 902-491-8605).

This research has been reviewed and cleared by the Saint Mary’s University Research Ethics Board. If you have any questions or concerns about ethical matters, you may contact the Saint Mary’s University Research Ethics board at ethics@smu.ca or (902) 420-5728; REB File# 23- 056.



CONSENT 

Please know that by participating in this research, you are not giving up any legal rights in the event that you are harmed during the research. By clicking the button to begin the survey, I understand that my participation is voluntary, I can withdraw from this study at any time without penalty, and I agree to participate in this study, titled: Do Canadians Understand the Risk of False Confessions?
